"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Matthew chapters 13–14
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-matthew-13-14.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/matthew.json
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/matthew.json (pre-existing: 13:11)

Key decisions in this range:
- Parable discourse (ch.13): classified as direct revelation — Jesus explains why he
  teaches in parables using Isa 6:9-10 (direct fulfillment) and cites "hidden since the
  foundation of the world" (Ps 78:2 as fulfillment)
- Kingdom parables: each classified as "revelation of God" showing Christ as the one
  who brings, embodies, and will judge the kingdom
- Hidden Treasure / Pearl (13:44-46): classified as revelation of God — the kingdom
  discovered costs all; Christ is both the finder and the treasure found
- Death of John (14:1-12): shadow — the prophet-herald dies before the king; mirror of
  what is coming for Jesus
- Feeding of 5000 (14:13-21): classified as type (Exodus manna) and fulfillment
  (Isa 25:6 messianic banquet); the eucharistic action formula connects to Last Supper
- Walking on water (14:25-33): classified as direct revelation — "I AM" (ego eimi)
  and the disciples' worship as "Son of God"
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: "That same day Jesus went out of the house and sat beside the sea." The shift from the house-setting of 12:46-50 (where Jesus redefined family as those who do the Father\'s will) to the open seashore marks the beginning of the Parable Discourse — the third of Matthew\'s five major discourses. Jesus sits (<em>ekathēto</em>) in the teacher\'s posture; the sea-setting and the great crowds following him mirror the opening of the Sermon on the Mount (5:1), where he also sat to teach. The location beside the sea recalls the Galilean calling-of-disciples scenes.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "And great crowds gathered about him, so that he got into a boat and sat there, and the whole crowd stood on the beach." The boat as teaching platform above the crowd creates both a practical acoustics solution and a symbolic distancing: Jesus teaches from the water\'s edge, between the land (the crowd) and the sea (the deep, representing the Gentile nations). The image of the teacher in the boat anticipates the later scene of walking on water (14:25-33) — the same sea, the same boat, a different dimension of revelation.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he told them many things in parables, saying: \'A sower went out to sow.\'" The transition to parabolic teaching is announced by Matthew as a new mode of address. The sower is a figure for the kingdom\'s work in the world, and Jesus is the Sower — the one who goes out to plant the word (v.37 identifies the Sower as the Son of Man). The parable begins with a universal activity (sowing) that disguises its eschatological freight: the scattering of seed is the scattering of the kingdom across the soil of the human heart.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "And as he sowed, some seeds fell along the path, and the birds came and devoured them." The path-soil represents hearts hardened by the traffic of ordinary life — impacted by the constant movement of concerns, anxieties, and distractions. The birds that devour the seed are identified in v.19 as the evil one; the Christological bearing: the proclamation of the kingdom creates immediate opposition at the spiritual level. The seed lost on the path is not a failed mission but a diagnostic of the variety of human reception of the kingdom.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "Other seeds fell on rocky ground, where they did not have much soil, and immediately they sprang up, since they had no depth of soil." The rocky ground represents shallow faith — initial enthusiasm without depth. The joy of immediate response without root anticipates the disciples\' failure at Gethsemane (26:40-43): shallow devotion cannot sustain the pressure of tribulation. The Christological pattern: Jesus\' ministry will consistently distinguish between surface reception and genuine discipleship, and tribulation will be the test that reveals the difference.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "But when the sun rose they were scorched. And since they had no root, they withered away." The sun that scorches the shallow-rooted plant is identified in v.21 as tribulation and persecution. The image of the plant that cannot survive the heat mirrors the disciples\' experience in the passion: those who had superficial attachment to Jesus will scatter when persecution comes (26:56). The Christological application: endurance requires depth of root — the deep root is union with Christ, who himself endured the full heat of divine wrath.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "Other seeds fell among thorns, and the thorns grew up and choked them." The thorns are identified in v.22 as the cares of the world and the deceitfulness of riches. The rich young ruler (19:16-22) is the narrative embodiment of thorn-soil: the word received but choked by attachment to wealth. The Christological bearing: the kingdom demands exclusive allegiance — the same demand that Jesus makes throughout the Gospel ("you cannot serve God and money," 6:24). Divided loyalty produces fruitlessness.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "Other seeds fell on good soil and produced grain, some a hundredfold, some sixty, some thirty." The hundredfold yield exceeds anything possible in normal agriculture (Isaac\'s hundredfold in Gen 26:12 was presented as miraculous); the yield of the kingdom is eschatological abundance. The three yields (hundredfold, sixty, thirty) suggest gradations of fruitfulness within genuine reception — not a single standard but a spectrum of response. The Christological frame: the good soil is those who hear, understand, and bear fruit (v.23), and fruitfulness is the mark of genuine discipleship (7:17-20).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "He who has ears, let him hear." The recurring call to hearing (7:26; 11:15; 13:43) frames the parables as requiring not merely auditory reception but interpretive engagement. The parabolic mode of teaching intentionally creates a gap between hearing and understanding that only genuine seeking can close (v.12: to the one who seeks, more is given). The Christological bearing: Jesus is the one who both speaks in parables and provides their interpretation to those who ask (vv. 10-23). He is simultaneously the teacher and the key to the teaching.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then the disciples came and said to him, \'Why do you speak to them in parables?\'" The disciples\' question is the hinge between the public parable and the private explanation. The Christological significance: the disciples, unlike the crowds, come to Jesus with the question. The seeking is itself the mark of belonging to the "you" to whom secrets are given (v.11). The community that gathers around Jesus and asks for understanding is the community of the kingdom — defined not by ethnic identity but by posture toward the teacher.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: "For to the one who has, more will be given, and he will have an abundance, but from the one who has not, even what he has will be taken away." The principle of abundance and privation in receiving kingdom revelation mirrors the pattern of stewardship throughout Matthew (25:29 repeats the principle in the parable of the talents). The Christological bearing: those who receive Christ receive "more" — the continuing work of the Spirit in understanding, the fellowship of the community, the eschatological inheritance. Those who reject Christ are left with less than they had.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "This is why I speak to them in parables, because seeing they do not see, and hearing they do not hear, nor do they understand." The explanation of the parabolic mode is rooted in Isa 6:9-10: parabolic speech both reveals to those who seek and conceals from those who have hardened. The parable is not a pedagogical device designed to teach everyone; it is an eschatological instrument that separates receptive from unreceptive soil. Jesus\' teaching method is itself part of the divine judgment on Israel\'s hardness.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "Indeed, in their case the prophecy of Isaiah is fulfilled that says: \'You will indeed hear but never understand, and you will indeed see but never perceive.\'" The citation of Isa 6:9 is Matthew\'s identification of the crowd\'s incomprehension as the fulfillment of the prophetic announcement. Isaiah\'s commission (Isa 6:8-13) was to preach to a nation that would not hear, hardening their hearts until judgment came. Jesus\' parabolic ministry to an unresponsive generation is the eschatological repetition of Isaiah\'s commission — and the judgment that follows will be Jerusalem\'s destruction (24:1-28).</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "For this people\'s heart has grown dull, and with their ears they can barely hear, and their eyes they have closed, lest they should see with their eyes and hear with their ears and understand with their heart and turn, and I would heal them." The citation of Isa 6:10 (LXX) with its final clause — "and I would heal them" — is a painful revelation: healing is available, healing is what Jesus offers throughout his ministry, but the hardened heart closes the organ through which healing would come. The Christological poignancy: the healer is present, but those who most need him have sealed themselves against receiving him.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct revelation: "But blessed are your eyes, for they see, and your ears, for they hear." The beatitude for seeing eyes and hearing ears is the positive counterpart to the Isaiah-fulfillment curse. The disciples who see and hear are not intrinsically superior to the crowd; they are those who have been given eyes and ears — who have sought understanding and received it. The Christological frame: what the disciples see and hear is the presence of the Son of God teaching the secrets of the kingdom, which prophets and righteous men longed to see.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: "For truly, I say to you, many prophets and righteous people longed to see what you see, and did not see it, and to hear what you hear, and did not hear it." The eschatological privilege of the disciples — seeing and hearing what prophets and righteous men desired — is a statement about the fulcrum of history. All of Israel\'s prophetic tradition was forward-pointing; the disciples stand at the point toward which it pointed. The one teaching them is the fulfillment of every prophetic longing, and their privilege is the gift of living in the time of fulfillment rather than anticipation.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "Hear then the parable of the sower." The command "hear" introduces the private explanation given to the inner circle — the transition from public parable to private interpretation. The dual-audience structure (parables for the crowd, explanations for the disciples) is the pattern of the kingdom: surface proclamation that conceals and a deeper teaching for those who seek. The Christological model: Jesus gives more to those who follow him into the private space of inquiry — discipleship is the posture that unlocks the teaching.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "When anyone hears the word of the kingdom and does not understand it, the evil one comes and snatches away what has been sown in his heart. This is what was sown along the path." The identification of the path-snatcher as the evil one establishes the parable as cosmic drama: the scattering of kingdom-seed is immediately contested by the adversary. The Christological frame: the word that is snatched is the word about the kingdom — which is ultimately the word about the King. Rejection of the kingdom message is spiritual warfare at the level of the heart.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "As for what was sown on rocky ground, this is the one who hears the word and immediately receives it with joy, yet he has no root in himself, but endures for a while, and when tribulation or persecution arises on account of the word, immediately he falls away." The rocky-ground believer fails precisely because of attachment to personal security rather than to Christ. The "on account of the word" signals that tribulation comes specifically because of alignment with Christ — the fellowship of suffering that Jesus will announce in 16:24-25. Rootedness is the key: only deep union with Christ sustains through persecution.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "Yet he has no root in himself, but endures for a while, and when tribulation or persecution arises on account of the word, immediately he falls away." The falling away (<em>skandalizetai</em>) is the same word used for the offense/stumbling of 11:6 ("blessed is the one who is not offended by me"). The rocky-ground person takes offense at tribulation — which is ultimately offense at the cross-shaped path of discipleship. The Christological diagnostic: those who receive Christ only when it is comfortable have not received him on his own terms.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "As for what was sown among thorns, this is the one who hears the word, but the cares of the world and the deceitfulness of riches choke the word, and it proves unfruitful." The thorn-soil failure is the failure of divided allegiance — the word received but not given exclusive claim on the heart. Jesus will embody the opposite: perfect poverty of spirit (8:20: "the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head") and undivided focus on the Father\'s will. Thorn-soil faith is the failure to follow the one who "sought first the kingdom of God" (6:33) in all things.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "As for what was sown on good soil, this is the one who hears the word and understands it. He indeed bears fruit and yields, in one case a hundredfold, in another sixty, and in another thirty." The good soil is defined by understanding (<em>synieis</em>) — the understanding that comes from following Jesus into the private space of inquiry (v.10-17). Understanding precedes fruitfulness; fruit is the evidence of genuine reception. The Christological chain: Christ gives understanding; understanding produces obedience; obedience bears fruit. The fruitful disciple is the one shaped by union with Christ the teacher.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "He put another parable before them, saying, \'The kingdom of heaven may be compared to a man who sowed good seed in his field.\'" The wheat-and-tares parable (explained in vv. 36-43) presents the kingdom\'s present reality: wheat and weeds growing together until the harvest. The Christological identification in v.37 — the Son of Man is the one who sows the good seed — positions Jesus as the author of the kingdom\'s planting in the world and the judge who will execute the final separation at the harvest.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: "But while his men were sleeping, his enemy came and sowed weeds among the wheat and went away." The adversary\'s counter-sowing in the night introduces the reality of spiritual opposition in the kingdom\'s present mixed state. The weeds (<em>zizania</em>, darnel) are indistinguishable from wheat until maturity — only at harvest can the separation be made. The Christological application: the community that gathers around Christ in this age will include both genuine and false disciples (cf. Judas among the twelve), and the final judgment will make the separation that human discernment cannot.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "So when the plants came up and bore grain, then the weeds appeared also." The delayed appearance of the weeds — visible only at maturity when fruit distinguishes them — mirrors the warning of 7:15-23: false prophets known by their fruit, false disciples exposed at the judgment. The Christological patience: the householder (Christ) chooses to wait for the harvest rather than prematurely uproot the field. The delay of judgment is an act of mercy toward the wheat — and a warning that the delay is temporary.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "And the servants of the master of the house came and said to him, \'Master, did you not sow good seed in your field? How then does it have weeds?\'" The servants\' question expresses the disciples\' theological puzzle: how does the kingdom, planted by the Son of Man, contain those who ultimately reject it? The parable answers this by identifying the adversary\'s counter-work. The Christological patience of the master (v.29: "let both grow together until the harvest") is the divine patience that Peter will later identify as the Lord\'s unwillingness that any should perish (2 Pet 3:9).</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: "He said to them, \'An enemy has done this.\' So the servants said to him, \'Then do you want us to go and gather them?\'" The servants\' eagerness to uproot the weeds is the understandable response to the presence of evil in the kingdom. The householder\'s refusal (v.29) reveals the divine economy: premature judgment risks destroying the wheat. The Christological application: the disciples are not authorized to perform the final separation (cf. 7:1-5) — that judgment belongs to the Son of Man at the end of the age (v.41).</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "But he said, \'No, lest in gathering the weeds you root up the wheat along with them.\'" The restraint of judgment protects genuine disciples from premature harm. The mixed field is the condition of the church in every age — those who belong to Christ alongside those who do not, indistinguishable to human observers. The Christological frame: the Son of Man\'s patience with the weeds is the same patience that allowed Judas to remain among the twelve until the appointed time. Judgment is deferred but not cancelled.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "Let both grow together until the harvest, and at harvest time I will tell the reapers, \'First collect the weeds and bind them in bundles to be burned, but gather the wheat into my barn.\'\'" The harvest at the end of the age is the Son of Man\'s work (v.41: he sends his angels). The barn (<em>apothēkē</em>) into which the wheat is gathered is the eschatological home of the redeemed — the kingdom prepared from the foundation of the world (25:34). The burning of the weeds is not the last word but the precondition for the wheat\'s safe gathering.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "He put another parable before them, saying, \'The kingdom of heaven is like a grain of mustard seed that a man took and sowed in his field.\'" The mustard seed parable presents the kingdom\'s apparent insignificance and its eventual global extent. The man who sows the seed is the Son of Man; the field is the world (v.38). The kingdom that begins with a small band of disciples in Galilee will expand to shelter "the birds of the air" — in the OT, a consistent image for the nations (Dan 4:12; Ezek 17:23; 31:6). The Great Commission is the mustard-seed dynamic in action.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: "It is the smallest of all seeds, but when it has grown it is larger than all the garden plants and becomes a tree, so that the birds of the air come and make nests in its branches." The great tree in which the birds nest echoes Daniel\'s vision (Dan 4:12: the great tree in which all living things find shelter) and Ezekiel\'s cedar (Ezek 17:22-24: YHWH\'s planting that becomes a noble cedar sheltering all birds). Christ\'s kingdom begins in the apparent weakness of incarnation, crucifixion, and a handful of disciples but becomes the tree that shelters the nations — the fulfillment of the Abrahamic promise (Gen 12:3: all nations blessed through Abraham\'s seed).</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "He told them another parable. \'The kingdom of heaven is like leaven that a woman took and hid in three measures of flour, till it was all leavened.\'" The leaven parable presents the kingdom\'s hidden but pervasive transformation. Three measures (<em>sata tria</em>) is a large batch — enough for an entire community feast. The woman hiding the leaven in the batch mirrors the divine hiddenness in the Incarnation: the Son of God hidden in human flesh, working through ordinary means to transform the whole. The kingdom transforms from within, invisibly, until the whole is changed.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "All these things Jesus said to the crowds in parables; indeed, he said nothing to them without a parable." Matthew\'s summary of the parabolic teaching method prepares for the fulfillment citation of v.35. The exclusive use of parables with the public is the pedagogical expression of the eschatological division: parables reveal and conceal simultaneously, giving the seeking heart a key and withholding that key from the hardened.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "This was to fulfill what was spoken by the prophet: \'I will open my mouth in parables; I will utter what has been hidden since the foundation of the world.\'" The citation of Ps 78:2 (attributed to "the prophet") identifies the parabolic discourse as the fulfillment of the Asaph psalm\'s opening. Ps 78 is a historical meditation on Israel\'s failures and YHWH\'s faithfulness; its "parables" are the hidden pattern of divine action in history. Jesus\' parables are the eschatological disclosure of what was hidden since creation — the mystery of the kingdom now revealed in the Son.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A revelation of God: "Then he left the crowds and went into the house. And his disciples came to him, saying, \'Explain to us the parable of the weeds of the field.\'" The movement from public teaching to private explanation mirrors the pattern of chs. 10-13: public proclamation followed by private instruction for those who seek. The disciples\' request for explanation is the act of seeking that is answered (v.12: "to the one who has, more will be given"). The explanation Jesus provides (vv. 37-43) is the most detailed allegorical interpretation in the parable discourse.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct revelation: "He answered, \'The one who sows the good seed is the Son of Man.\'" The Son of Man as the sower identifies Jesus as the one who planted the community of the kingdom in the world. The title "Son of Man" here carries both the Danielic weight of eschatological authority (Dan 7:13-14) and the earthly mission of the incarnate one. The good seed he sows is the "sons of the kingdom" (v.38) — those who genuinely belong to the King. The agricultural metaphor gives way to personal identification: the sower is not an abstract principle but the specific person of Jesus Christ.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A revelation of God: "The field is the world, and the good seed is the sons of the kingdom. The weeds are the sons of the evil one." The world as the field expands the scope beyond Israel: the kingdom\'s planting is global from the beginning, not merely national. The "sons of the kingdom" (<em>huioi tēs basileias</em>) are those who belong to the King — the same phrase used in 8:12 for those who should have been in the kingdom but were excluded. The two categories — sons of the kingdom and sons of the evil one — are the eschatological division made visible at the harvest.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A direct revelation: "The enemy who sowed them is the devil. The harvest is the end of the age, and the reapers are angels." The identification of the enemy as the devil connects the parable to the cosmological conflict that runs throughout Matthew (4:1-11: the temptation; 12:28-29: the binding of the strong man). The harvest at the end of the age is the final act of that conflict — the devil\'s work undone, the weeds gathered, the wheat secured. The angels as reapers appear again in 24:31 (gathering the elect at the Son of Man\'s coming).</p>',
    "40": '<p>A direct revelation: "Just as the weeds are gathered and burned with fire, so will it be at the end of the age." The fire of judgment that burns the weeds is the same fire announced by John the Baptist (3:12: "he will burn the chaff with unquenchable fire") and anticipated in the Sermon on the Mount (5:22; 7:19). The end of the age is not a distant theoretical possibility but the fixed point toward which all of Jesus\' eschatological teaching is oriented. Christ is the one who names this end and who will preside over it.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A direct revelation: "The Son of Man will send his angels, and they will gather out of his kingdom all causes of sin and all law-breakers." The Son of Man sending angels is the eschatological role of Dan 7:13-14 made concrete. The Son of Man\'s kingdom contains both wheat and weeds until the harvest; the purging of "all causes of sin and all law-breakers" is the completion of the kingdom\'s purification. This is the positive counterpart to the negative judgment: the kingdom is not just about excluding the wicked but about perfecting the community of the redeemed.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A direct revelation: "And throw them into the fiery furnace. In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth." The fiery furnace (<em>kaminon tou pyros</em>) echoes Dan 3 (the furnace into which Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego were thrown, from which the Son of God delivered them). The Christological irony: the furnace that was the site of divine deliverance in Daniel becomes the site of final judgment — because the one who delivered from fire is now the judge who sends into fire. Those who refuse the deliverer receive the full weight of the judgment he bore.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A direct revelation: "Then the righteous will shine like the sun in the kingdom of their Father. He who has ears, let him hear." The shining of the righteous echoes Dan 12:3 ("those who are wise shall shine like the brightness of the sky above"). The kingdom of "their Father" — the Father whom Jesus has revealed (11:27) — is the eschatological home prepared for those who are the Son\'s. The inheritance of the Father\'s kingdom is the final form of the adoption that Christ makes possible (5:9: "they shall be called sons of God").</p>',
    "44": '<p>A revelation of God: "The kingdom of heaven is like treasure hidden in a field, which a man found and covered up. Then in his joy he goes and sells all that he has and buys that field." The Hidden Treasure parable has a double Christological reading: the kingdom is the treasure for which the disciple sells all; but Christ is also the one who finds his treasure (the redeemed) hidden in the field of the world, sells all he has (empties himself, Phil 2:7), and purchases the field. Both readings are valid: the disciple gives all for Christ, and Christ gives all for his people. The joy of both transactions is the key — the kingdom is not acquired by reluctant duty but by joyful expenditure.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A revelation of God: "Again, the kingdom of heaven is like a merchant in search of fine pearls." The Pearl parable parallels the Hidden Treasure but with a difference: the merchant is actively searching, the finder stumbles upon the treasure. Both patterns of kingdom-encounter are real — the seeker and the surprised. In both cases, the possession of the kingdom costs everything. The Christological bearing: Christ is simultaneously the merchant who sought the pearl (the redeemed, for whom he paid everything) and the pearl of great price for which the disciple sells all.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A revelation of God: "Who, on finding one pearl of great value, went and sold all that he had and bought it." The totality of the sacrifice — "all that he had" — is the kingdom\'s demand in parabolic form. Matthew 19:21 (the rich young ruler: "sell all you have") is the explicit application; 16:24 (take up your cross) is the structural principle. The pearl found worth selling all is ultimately the person of Christ — the one in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge (Col 2:3).</p>',
    "47": '<p>A revelation of God: "Again, the kingdom of heaven is like a net that was thrown into the sea and gathered fish of every kind." The Net parable is the eschatological counterpart to the Wheat and Tares: both present a mixed community now and a final separation at the end. The net gathers from the sea — the realm of the Gentile nations in OT symbolism — and brings in "every kind," anticipating the Great Commission\'s gathering of "all nations" (28:19). The kingdom\'s gathering is universal and indiscriminate in this age; the separation is the work of the age to come.</p>',
    "48": '<p>A revelation of God: "When it was full, men drew it ashore and sat down and sorted the good into containers but threw away the bad." The sorting of fish mirrors the separation of wheat and weeds (vv. 30, 40-43) and anticipates the judgment of the sheep and goats (25:31-46). The good fish collected in containers are the eschatological harvest of the righteous; the bad thrown away are those whose condition is revealed only at the moment of judgment. The parable does not specify who the sorters are — v.49 identifies them as angels, as in v.41.</p>',
    "49": '<p>A direct revelation: "So it will be at the end of the age. The angels will come out and separate the evil from the righteous." The third eschatological judgment parable in this discourse (wheat/tares, v.40-43; fiery furnace, v.42; net, v.49-50) underscores the certainty and universality of the final separation. The angels\' role is consistent: they execute the Son of Man\'s judgment (v.41) rather than originating it. The "end of the age" (<em>synteleia tou aiōnos</em>) is the fixed eschatological point that gives the parabolic series its urgency.</p>',
    "50": '<p>A direct revelation: "And throw them into the fiery furnace. In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth." The repeated "weeping and gnashing of teeth" formula (7:12; 8:12; 13:42, 50; 22:13; 24:51; 25:30) is Matthew\'s consistent eschatological refrain. The Christological weight: the same voice that says "come to me, all who are weary, and I will give you rest" (11:28) also says "weeping and gnashing of teeth." The gentleness of the invitation and the severity of the rejection-consequence belong to the same person. The invitation is as total as the warning.</p>',
    "51": '<p>A revelation of God: "Have you understood all these things?" They said to him, \'Yes.\'" The disciples\' affirmation of understanding — however incomplete it turns out to be — is the culmination of the private teaching session. The understanding given to the disciples (v.11: "to you it has been given to know the secrets") is confirmed by their own acknowledgment. The Christological pedagogy: Jesus does not simply teach content but forms the disciples\' capacity for understanding — an ongoing process that will require the Spirit\'s further work after the resurrection.</p>',
    "52": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he said to them, \'Therefore every scribe who has been trained for the kingdom of heaven is like a master of a house who brings out of his treasure what is new and what is old.\'" The scribe trained for the kingdom — bringing both old and new from the treasury — is the model disciple who has received Jesus\' teaching as the fulfillment of all that came before. The Christological frame: Jesus is the master of the house whose treasury is both the Scriptures (the old) and the kingdom\'s new revelation. The trained disciple distributes both under his authority.</p>',
    "53": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when Jesus had finished these parables, he went away from there." The closing formula of the third discourse (paralleling 7:28; 11:1; 19:1; 26:1) marks the completion of the Parable Discourse. The departure from the seashore back toward Galilee prepares for the rejection at Nazareth (vv. 54-58), which follows immediately: the parabolic teaching about reception and rejection is immediately illustrated by the hometown\'s refusal.</p>',
    "54": '<p>A revelation of God: "And coming to his hometown he taught them in their synagogue, so that they were astonished, and said, \'Where did this man get this wisdom and these mighty works?\'" The astonishment of Jesus\' hometown carries the note of the parable-discourse ironically: they are astonished but not converted. The question "where did this man get..." is the right question with the wrong presupposition: they expect the answer to be a human source, but the wisdom and works come from the Father (11:27). The astonishment that does not lead to faith is the rocky-ground response of 13:20-21.</p>',
    "55": '<p>A revelation of God: "Is not this the carpenter\'s son? Is not his mother called Mary? And are not his brothers James and Joseph and Simon and Judas?" The hometown\'s objection is based on ordinary knowledge: they know his family, his trade, his background. The familiarity that should have been a privilege becomes a barrier — the extraordinary in the ordinary is invisible to those who know only the ordinary. The Christological scandal of the Incarnation: the Son of God takes on such ordinary human existence that those closest to his humanity cannot perceive his divinity.</p>',
    "56": '<p>A revelation of God: "And are not all his sisters with us? Where then did this man get all these things?" The sisters\' presence in Nazareth — unnamed, unspecified in number — completes the catalog of Jesus\' ordinariness. The question "where did this man get all these things?" is the repeated question of the Gospels, and its answer is the Gospel itself: from the Father, through the Spirit, as the incarnate Son. Those who know his human origins exclusively cannot receive the answer.</p>',
    "57": '<p>A direct revelation: "And they took offense at him. But Jesus said to them, \'A prophet is not without honor except in his hometown and in his own household.\'" The prophetic identification of Jesus\' experience — the prophet dishonored at home — is both a self-identification with the prophetic tradition and a Christological claim that exceeds it. Jesus is more than a prophet (11:9: "more than a prophet"), but the pattern of rejection that afflicts the prophet afflicts him fully. The hometown rejection is the miniature passion: his own people do not receive him (John 1:11).</p>',
    "58": '<p>A revelation of God: "And he did not do many mighty works there, because of their unbelief." The limitation of miracles by unbelief is not a limitation of Jesus\' power but of the relational dynamic in which his power operates. Faith is the appropriate reception of the one who offers the kingdom; unbelief closes the channel. The Christological bearing: the healing and miracle-working of Jesus is not a demonstration of raw divine power but a relational gift — given to those who receive the giver, withheld not by incapacity but by the integrity of the relationship.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>A shadow: "At that time Herod the tetrarch heard about the fame of Jesus." Herod Antipas — son of Herod the Great, tetrarch of Galilee and Perea — hears about Jesus\' ministry. The hearing is ominous: it is Herod who imprisoned John the Baptist and will soon behead him. The Christological shadow: the political power that silenced the herald will ultimately bring Jesus before a member of the Herodian dynasty at his trial (Luke 23:7-12). The king and the prophet are linked in their reception by the powers of this age.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A shadow: "And he said to his servants, \'This is John the Baptist. He has been raised from the dead; that is why these miraculous powers are at work in him.\'" Herod\'s guilty conscience interprets Jesus\' ministry as John the Baptist\'s resurrection — a theologically ironic error. He perceives resurrection power in Jesus but attributes it to the wrong person. The Christological irony: Herod is half-right; there is resurrection power at work in Jesus, but it is the power of the Son of God, not a resurrected prophet. The rumors of resurrection will become the actual resurrection that Herod and Pilate will conspire to suppress (28:11-15).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A shadow: "For Herod had seized John and bound him and put him in prison for the sake of Herodias, his brother Philip\'s wife." The imprisonment of John — the herald who prepared the way — on account of his faithful proclamation mirrors the fate that awaits Jesus. John spoke truth to power (v.4: "it is not lawful for you to have her"); the political-religious nexus silenced him. The pattern of the prophet silenced by power is the pattern of the passion, and John\'s fate is the prologue to Jesus\' own trial and execution.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A shadow: "Because John had been saying to him, \'It is not lawful for you to have her.\'" John\'s indictment of Herod\'s marriage to his brother\'s wife was based on Lev 18:16 (a man shall not uncover his brother\'s wife\'s nakedness). The faithful prophet who speaks the truth of the covenant to a ruler who violates it is the OT pattern from Nathan before David (2 Sam 12:7) to Elijah before Ahab (1 Kgs 18:18). John follows this line; Jesus will follow it more completely before Pilate.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "And though he wanted to put him to death, he feared the people, because they held him to be a prophet." The political calculation — wanting to kill but fearing the crowds who honor the prophet — exactly mirrors the chief priests\' calculation in Jerusalem (21:46; 26:5). The pattern is not coincidental: both John and Jesus are protected temporarily by popular support, and both are eventually killed by the same combination of political pressure, private hostility, and crowd manipulation. The political mechanics of the passion are rehearsed in miniature in John\'s death.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A shadow: "But when Herod\'s birthday came, the daughter of Herodias danced before the company and pleased Herod." The birthday banquet that occasions the death of the prophet is a dark mirror of the eschatological banquet (8:11; 22:1-14) — the kingdom\'s feast perverted into the occasion for prophetic execution. The cultural resonance of the birthday feast (a Roman custom associated with excess) contrasts with the Passover context of Jesus\' death. Both prophetic deaths occur in the context of festive meals where political power overrides justice.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A shadow: "So that he promised with an oath to give her whatever she might ask." Herod\'s oath — made rashly at a banquet — mirrors the foolish oaths of the OT (Jephthah\'s vow, Judg 11:30-31; Saul\'s oath, 1 Sam 14:24-45). The oath that cannot be undone without loss of face is the mechanism of John\'s death. The Christological shadow: rash oaths made in contexts of social pressure lead to prophetic deaths. Jesus warned against oaths (5:33-37) precisely because their absolutism can override justice and wisdom.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A shadow: "Prompted by her mother, she said, \'Give me the head of John the Baptist here on a platter.\'" The demand for the head — immediate, graphic, non-negotiable — is orchestrated by Herodias who had wanted John dead (Mark 6:19). The dance, the oath, and the demand are a chain of events in which each link was set by Herodias and executed through her daughter. The Christological shadow: the death of the prophet is engineered by those who fear the truth he speaks. The comparison with the chief priests who engineer Jesus\' death through Judas is direct.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A shadow: "And the king was sorry, but because of his oaths and his guests he commanded it to be given." Herod\'s grief — he does not want John dead — but his compliance with the demand because of social pressure and the oath he cannot retract, mirrors Pilate\'s reluctance and compliance in 27:18-26 (he knows Jesus is innocent but gives in to the crowd\'s demand). The pattern of the sympathetic but complicit ruler is repeated in both deaths. Social pressure and political face overcome the private judgment of the ruler.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A shadow: "He sent and had John beheaded in the prison." The beheading of John — a Roman-style execution appropriate for political prisoners — concludes the prophetic career of the herald. John had announced "I am not worthy to carry his sandals" (3:11); his death prepares the way for the one who will die publicly, on a cross, before the crowds. John\'s death is the private execution of the herald; Jesus\' death will be the public execution of the king. Both are unjust; both serve the redemptive purpose of the Father.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A shadow: "His head was brought on a platter and given to the girl, and she brought it to her mother." The trophy of John\'s head, carried to the one who demanded it, is the final image of prophetic death as political trophy. The Christological resonance: the body of Jesus will be requested from Pilate after the crucifixion (27:58) — the same movement of a man\'s body from execution to petitioner. But where Herodias requested the head as a trophy of silence, Joseph of Arimathea requests the body as an act of honor.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A shadow: "And his disciples came and took the body and buried it, and they went and told Jesus." The disciples\' act of burial and the report to Jesus frames John\'s death as the immediate context for Jesus\' withdrawal (v.13). The disciples of John inform the one who John announced; the death of the herald is communicated to the one who is heralded. The Christological connection: Jesus\' response to John\'s death (withdrawal to a desolate place) is the response of the one who knows that the herald\'s fate is the preview of his own.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "Now when Jesus heard this, he withdrew from there in a boat to a desolate place by himself. But when the crowds heard it, they followed him on foot from the towns." The withdrawal after hearing of John\'s death is both a human response to grief and a strategic retreat before the political danger (Herod\'s attention has turned toward miracle-workers, v.1-2). The crowd\'s persistent following — even around the lake on foot — is the measure of their need: they pursue him despite his withdrawal. His compassion for them (v.14) overrides his own need for solitude.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "When he went ashore he saw a great crowd, and he had compassion on them and healed their sick." The compassion of Jesus for the crowd — who have followed him into the wilderness without food — is the fulfillment of Ezek 34:16 (YHWH, the divine shepherd, healing the sick among the scattered flock). The healings in the wilderness context also echo the wilderness healings of the Exodus generation (Ps 105:37). Christ is the divine shepherd who does not dismiss the need even when he himself has withdrawn from the crowds.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A type: "Now when it was evening, the disciples came to him and said, \'This is a desolate place, and the day is now over; send the crowds away to go into the villages and buy food for themselves.\'" The disciples\' pragmatic solution — send them away — is the human response to an impossible situation. The wilderness, the evening, the hungry crowd, and the disciples\' inadequate resources are all elements of the Exodus manna narrative (Num 11:13: "Where am I to get meat to give to all this people?"). The stage is set for the provision that only God could make.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct revelation: "But Jesus said, \'They need not go away; you give them something to eat.\'" The command to the disciples — "you give them something to eat" — places the impossible demand on them before Jesus provides through them. The Christological pattern: Christ first places the disciples in the position of inadequacy, then works through their hands. The feeding is not done by Jesus alone but through his distribution through the disciples — the pattern of the church\'s ministry: receiving from Christ and distributing to the hungry.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A type: "They said to him, \'We have only five loaves here and two fish.\'" The five loaves and two fish are the concrete inventory of inadequacy — the exact measure of human insufficiency before the divine provision. The Christological bearing: Christ uses what is given, however little, and multiplies it beyond any natural possibility. The specific numbers (five loaves, two fish) are not allegorical but historical; the miracle\'s power is in the specificity of the inadequate provision transformed by the Son\'s blessing.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A type: "And he said, \'Bring them here to me.\'" The instruction "bring them here to me" is the posture of all Christ\'s provision: inadequate resources brought to him become sufficient through him. The Christological principle applied to discipleship: whatever the disciple has — however little — brought to Christ becomes the material of kingdom provision. The feeding miracle teaches not just about miraculous power but about the economy of discipleship: give what you have to the Son, who multiplies it for the many.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A type and fulfillment: "Then he ordered the crowds to sit down on the grass, and taking the five loaves and the two fish, he looked up to heaven and said a blessing. Then he broke the loaves and gave them to the disciples, and the disciples gave them to the crowds." The four eucharistic actions — took, blessed, broke, gave — are identical to the Last Supper formula (26:26) and the Emmaus road recognition (Luke 24:30). The Exodus feeding (manna from heaven) and the Last Supper are both anticipated here: the wilderness meal is both the fulfillment of the Exodus type and the preview of the eucharistic institution. Christ feeds the five thousand as a type of his own body broken for the world.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A type: "And they all ate and were satisfied. And they took up twelve baskets full of the broken pieces left over." The abundance — all satisfied, twelve baskets remaining — is the signature of the divine feeding in the OT: YHWH provides more than enough (Ps 78:25: "the bread of the angels" that satisfied the wilderness generation; 2 Kgs 4:42-44: Elisha feeding 100 with twenty loaves and having leftovers). The twelve baskets connect to the twelve disciples, the twelve tribes of Israel, and the eschatological banquet that feeds all peoples. The kingdom provision is superabundant.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A type: "And those who ate were about five thousand men, besides women and children." The scale of the feeding — five thousand men, plus women and children (implying perhaps 10,000-20,000 total) — establishes the miracle as a public, massive act of provision. The numbers recall the Exodus generation (600,000 men at the Exodus, Num 11:21); the feeding in the wilderness is the new Exodus feeding. The one who provides is the new Moses, but also more than Moses: Moses asked YHWH for meat; Jesus provides from what is given to him, by his own blessing.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "Immediately he made the disciples get into the boat and go before him to the other side, while he dismissed the crowds." The immediate compulsion of the disciples to the boat — Jesus separating them from the crowd — mirrors John\'s account (John 6:15) where the crowd attempts to make Jesus king by force after the feeding. Jesus withdraws the disciples before the political pressure to become a different kind of king than he is. The Christological tension: he feeds the five thousand but refuses to be the bread-king the crowd wants.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "And after he had dismissed the crowds, he went up on the mountain by himself to pray. When evening came, he was there alone." Jesus\' retreat to the mountain for solitary prayer is the pattern of his life with the Father: the mountain as the place of divine encounter (5:1; 17:1; 28:16). The solitary prayer in the evening mirrors Moses alone on Sinai and Elijah alone on Horeb. But Jesus does not go to the mountain to receive the law or the prophetic word; he goes as the Son who communes with the Father. Prayer is the constant rhythm of his human life with God.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "But the boat by this time was a long way from the land, beaten by the waves, for the wind was against them." The disciples in the boat, beaten by the waves and fighting the wind, are the image of the church in its mission: making progress against resistance without the immediate visible presence of Christ. The night storm between the two feeding miracles frames the church\'s condition in this age: the bread has been given, the Lord has withdrawn to prayer, and the disciples are struggling against the elements until he comes.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation: "And in the fourth watch of the night he came to them, walking on the sea." Walking on the sea is a divine prerogative in the OT: Job 9:8 ("who alone stretched out the heavens and trampled the waves of the sea") and Job 38:16 ("Have you entered into the springs of the sea, or walked in the recesses of the deep?") both attribute sea-walking to YHWH alone. Jesus walking on the water is a theophanic act — the display of the Creator\'s authority over his creation. The timing (fourth watch, 3-6 AM) is the darkest hour before dawn.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "But when the disciples saw him walking on the sea, they were terrified, and said, \'It is a ghost!\' and they cried out in fear." The disciples\' terror is the standard OT response to theophany — the overwhelming of human senses before the divine presence. They misidentify the theophanic figure as a ghost (<em>phantasma</em>, appearance, specter) — a category error that Jesus corrects in v.27. The fear is appropriate to the encounter; the misidentification is the failure to recognize the one they have been following.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: "But immediately Jesus spoke to them, saying, \'Take heart; it is I (<em>egō eimi</em>). Do not be afraid.\'" The <em>egō eimi</em> ("I AM") is the divine self-disclosure formula of Exod 3:14 (YHWH\'s name to Moses) and the Johannine "I AM" sayings (John 8:58; 18:5-6). Combined with "Do not be afraid" — the standard angel-of-the-LORD greeting (1:20; 28:5; Gen 26:24; Isa 41:10) — the verse identifies Jesus as YHWH who speaks to his people in their fear. The one walking on the water is not a ghost but the divine "I AM" in human form.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: "And Peter answered him, \'Lord, if it is you, command me to come to you on the water.\'" Peter\'s request — "command me" — is the posture of faith in the theophanic presence. He does not presume to walk on water by his own will but asks for the word of command from the one who has authority over the water. The Christological bearing: the disciple can only do what Christ commands; Peter\'s walking on water is possible only because Christ says "come." The disciples\' participation in the miraculous is always derivative — dependent on the word of the Lord.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct revelation: "He said, \'Come.\' So Peter got out of the boat and walked on the water and came to Jesus." Peter walking on water is the miraculous participation that flows from Christ\'s command. The walking is real and physical; Peter\'s feet on the water are a participation in what Jesus is doing, by his authority. The Christological extension: the disciples are not observers of the miraculous but participants in it, when they act on Christ\'s word. The miracle of Peter\'s walking is not his own achievement but the extension of Christ\'s theophanic authority.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "But when he saw the wind, he was frightened and beginning to sink he cried out, \'Lord, save me.\'" The transition from walking to sinking — when Peter\'s attention moves from Christ to the wind — is the paradigm of faith and doubt. The wind and waves are real; the doubt is not irrational. But the one who commands the wind (8:26) is more real than the wind. Peter\'s cry "Lord, save me" (<em>Kyrie, sōson me</em>) is the exact formula of the Psalms of lament — and it is sufficient. The Christological response: the Lord who commands the sea saves the one who sinks in it.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A direct revelation: "Jesus immediately reached out his hand and took hold of him, saying to him, \'O you of little faith, why did you doubt?\'" The immediate hand of rescue — the same hand that healed the leper (8:3) and raised Jairus\'s daughter (9:25) — reaches into the water for the sinking disciple. The "little faith" charge is not condemnation but diagnosis and invitation: the faith that walked on water was real, and the doubt that caused the sinking is the obstacle to its completion. The rescue is unconditional; the question is the call to greater faith.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A direct revelation: "And when they got into the boat, the wind ceased." The stilling of the wind at Jesus\' entry into the boat completes the theophanic sequence: he walks on water, he reaches for the sinking disciple, and the wind ceases at his presence. The same pattern as 8:26 — the rebuke of wind and sea — is repeated without a word: the wind ceases because he enters the space where it had been raging. His presence is the calm; his absence is the storm. The Christological principle of presence: where Christ is, the storm ceases.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A direct revelation: "And those in the boat worshiped him, saying, \'Truly you are the Son of God.\'" The disciples\' worship and confession — "truly you are the Son of God" — is the first full Christological confession in Matthew before Caesarea Philippi (16:16). It is provoked not by teaching but by theophany: the walking on water and the stilling of the wind have disclosed what words have not yet named. The worship (<em>prosekunēsan</em>) is the correct response to the theophanic "I AM"; the confession is the crystallization of everything the disciples have seen. The Son of God is present.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when they had crossed over, they came to land at Gennesaret." The arrival at Gennesaret — a fertile plain on the northwest shore of the Sea of Galilee — is the transition back to the public ministry of healing. The movement from the theophanic sea-crossing to the ordinary work of healing shows the pattern of Jesus\' life: the mountain-prayer, the sea-walking theophany, and then the routine but compassionate healing ministry. The extraordinary revelation does not replace but undergirds the ordinary ministry.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "And when the men of that place recognized him, they sent around to all that region and brought to him all who were sick." The recognition of Jesus at Gennesaret — and the immediate dispatch to gather the sick from the whole region — shows the cumulative effect of his healing ministry: his fame has spread, the expectation is established, and those who know of his power bring him the sick. The network of need and supply is functioning: those who have experienced his healing send for those who need it. The kingdom\'s reach extends through those who have received it.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "And implored him that they might only touch the fringe of his garment. And as many as touched it were made well." The echoing of the hemorrhaging woman\'s faith (9:21) at a regional scale — the whole region coming to touch the fringe — shows the pattern established in ch. 9 becoming a movement. The fringe of the garment (the tassels commanded in Num 15:38-40) as the point of contact between the Messiah and the sick embodies the Christological logic: the covenant promise in him is the source of healing, and faith in his person is sufficient contact to receive it. The "as many as touched" is the plural form of the individual miracle.</p>'
  }
}

